1C9O | Sperm Whale MyoglobinBiological Role: While hemoglobin transports oxygen through the bloodstream, myoglobin acts as the primary oxygen storage unit in muscle tissues. It is found in high concentrations in diving mammals (like the sperm whale), allowing them to store large reserves of oxygen to survive underwater for extended periods.Structural Mechanics: Unlike hemoglobin, myoglobin is a compact, monomeric protein (consisting of just a single polypeptide chain) made of eight alpha-helices. It contains a single heme group. Because the 1C9O crystal was grown and imaged to an ultra-high resolution of $0.97 \text{ \AA}$, it maps out the exact electronic coordinates of individual atoms, showing precisely how the protein backbone holds the iron-containing heme pocket stable.
